<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Joint Committee on the Draft Deregulation Bill</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Rail North – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Our interest is in the devolution of responsibilities for rail services to the north of England so as to better align decision-making on transport and wider economic development.  These plans are especially relevant given that one of the overall aims of the Draft Deregulation Bill is to promote economic growth.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Background</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In response to a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> consultation on devolution of decision-making in rail franchising in 2012 north of England local authorities made proposals to devolve decision-making for railways in the North to the North.  Currently most responsibilities for rail services in the North lie in Westminster.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The over-riding objective of the authorities is to promote the growth and prosperity of the North of England economy through development of rail services, and at the same time make decision-making more democratic and efficient.  During 2013 north of England local authorities agreed to a “Prospectus” setting out their objectives for railways in the North, and how they would work together to make decisions.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Rail </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">North</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> has been created to lead this work on behalf of the North of England authorities.  In August 2013, and at the Department of Transport’s request, Rail North submitted a formal “Proposition and Business Case” for devolution in the context of the imminent re-franchising of the rail services currently operated by </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">TransPennine</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Express and Northern Rail.  This proposition details the work we have carried out on the legal underpinnings and organisational design of the new structures.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Devolution and decision-making proposals</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Government policy in recent years has increasingly devolved decision-making in order to promote stronger economic growth and more efficient decision-making.  The North has taken the lead in many of these changes.  Over half of the first </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">wave of the government’s “city deals” have</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> been with Northern conurbations – the momentum of this programme is now being replicated in another five areas in the North.  The bigger cities of the North are reforming their own governance through the creation of new simpler conurbation-wide “combined authorities” – all of which have transport powers (through the Local Democracy, Economic Development and Construction Act, 2009).  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Our plans for rail devolution in the North set out how the authorities </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">North</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> will make decisions together.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is proposed that direction is set by a North of England Leaders’ Committee, and implemented through by a newly constituted Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV).  In practice this SPV would act through an Executive Board, with a small Executive team reporting to it.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The overall decision-making structures must be capable of taking financial responsibilities and have a substantial capacity to manage and bear risk.  The SPV’s members will be local authorities with transport authority powers.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The local transport authorities (LTAs) in the North include in metropolitan areas, a combined authority and 4 integrated transport authorities (ITAs) (some or all of which </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">are likely to be replaced by combined authorities).  All of these authorities currently have passenger transport executives (PTEs) which act as their executive body.  Outside metropolitan areas, the LTAs are the county councils and unitary authorities.  In order for us to pursue these plans, the constituent members of the SPV will require the necessary statutory powers to specify and manage rail services, and the benefit of a franchise exemption order under section 24 of the Railway Act 1993 exempting rail services in the North from the national franchising regime.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">However the existing legislation restricts the ability of the constituent authorities through the SPV to carry out its proposals.  In particular:  </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The powers of Passenger Transport Executives under the Transport Act 1968 to carry passengers by rail is limited to a geographic area that may extend no further than 25 miles from their boundary; whereas the Rail North proposition covers a much wider geography; and,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Railways Act 1993 contains specific provisions which give the Secretary of State </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">powers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and protections in relation to franchises within the national franchising regime.  However, these are not available to LTAs and PTEs where rail services have been exempted from that regime (e.g. around breach of the terms of a franchise).  We would like LTAs and PTEs to be able to make use of these powers.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The draft Deregulation Bill (section 22 and schedule 7) is very welcome in that it removes restrictions and addresses these issues.  We believe it therefore paves the way for devolution of rail provision, and a more efficient way of procuring rail services in the north of England in the future.  Appendix 1 sets out some more specific observations and proposals for how the Deregulation Bill could be modified.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This submission focuses on the generic provisions of the bill.  Comments on the questions the committee has tabled are set out in Appendix 2.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">16 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix 1:  Specific comments on draft Deregulation Bill in order to promote rail devolution to the North of England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The provisions in the Deregulation Bill that relate to rail devolution are contained within section </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">22 and Schedule 7.  In order to deliver the rail devolution agenda for the North, Local Transport Authorities would need to have the following powers:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to form an accountable corporate body capable of contracting with other authorities, Government and Rail Operators;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to provide or procure rail passenger services under the Transport Acts across the geography of the area; and,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> have the benefit of an exemption order from the Railways Act 1993 franchising provisions whilst retaining various powers and protections enjoyed by the Secretary of State under those provisions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">All authorities currently have the first power.  However, in the metropolitan areas of Greater Manchester, Merseyside, South Yorkshire, Tyne and Wear and West Yorkshire, the second power is potentially restricted by the 25 mile limit on the exercise of their PTE’s </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">power to carry or procure the carriage of passengers by rail.  This restriction is anomalous, since LTAs outside metropolitan areas which have no PTE do not have this restriction and can use their general power of competence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">As regards the third power for rail devolution to work practically, it is important that LTAs and PTEs which manage services exempted from the national franchising regime should enjoy the benefits of some of the powers and protections in relation to any operating agreement enjoyed by the Secretary of State in relation to franchised services.  The existing legislation does not allow this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The provisions of the Deregulation Bill will address these legislative obstacles by giving authorities most of the requisite remaining powers, and is therefore welcomed.  There are some observations to be made however:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> power to provide rail substitution bus services should also benefit from the removal of the 25 mile restriction, so that it corresponds with the relevant rail power.  We would suggest an appropriate amendment to the 1985 Transport Act:</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">in view of the likely SPV being a company limited by guarantee jointly owned by several local transport authorities or their PTEs, we would recommend that Section 24A(4)(c)(iii) be amended to say “any company wholly owned by a person </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">or jointly owned by persons </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">falling within sub paragraph (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">) or (ii)”;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">it is unclear why the proposed s24A(2) does not permit the Secretary of State also to make orders under s24 which correspond to s27(4) (restriction on disposal by franchisee of wholly owned subsidiaries providing services); and,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> would want to ensure that the draft bill does not lead to any unintended consequences where new Combined Aut</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">horities are to be set up.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix 2:  Comments of suggested questions </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">General </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The draft Bill covers a broad range of specific activities and a large amount of legislative provision is amended by it. Could the same result have been achieved using existing secondary legislative procedures? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It is our opinion that the changes in powers that we seek cannot be achieved through secondary legislation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">What are the advantages and disadvantages of including specific deregulatory provisions amending existing legislation and providing additional or amended order making powers within primary legislation rather than considering them through existing deregulatory mechanisms? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The changes in powers that we seek will provide the most robust underpinning for the operation of the proposed devolved decision-making structures.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Are the changes proposed in the draft Bill evidence-based and have any risks associated with the changes been taken adequately into account? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">N/a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">4. Does the draft Bill achieve its purpose of reducing the regulatory burden on business, organisations and individuals effectively and fairly? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Yes.  Our proposals will lead to better prioritisation of national and local resources into rail service provision.  The legislation removes unnecessary restrictions in the Transport Act 1968 and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the  Railways</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Act 1993.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">5. Will the draft Bill generally benefit businesses by offsetting other regulatory burdens?  Are there indirect impacts on other businesses from reducing regulation in specific sectors? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">No significant issues arising.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">6. To what extent does the draft Bill benefit consumers as well as businesses? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The use of the powers the bill contains will enable rail services to be managed closer to the beneficiary, whether that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">be</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> local businesses or rail passengers.  We fully expect this will lead to better services that more closely match their needs.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">7. How does the provision in the draft Bill affect: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. protections afforded to individuals under human rights and equalities legislation? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ii. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">employment</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> law, skills and the labour market? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">iii. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> environment, particularly in the management of waste? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">iv. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> provision of education? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">v</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. the effective administration of justice? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">vi. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">social</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, wellbeing or health inequalities? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">No significant impacts. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-inde